        {
            "title": "TUSSEN WAL EN SCHIP: A quest for finding home and self-identity",
            "date": {
                "start": {
                    "month": 8,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2017
                },
                "end": {
                    "month": null,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": null
                }
            },
            "description": "Critical awareness towards the impact that European colonialism had on shaping South Africa and the identity of contemporary white South Africans is what drove this project. This hand tufted and beaded carpet mirror my own position within the world and are a reaction to my own feelings of not belonging and being lost somewhere \u2018tussen wal en schip\u2019. It highlights the complex colonial connection and history that too often goes unacknowledged, is misunderstood, and is often intentionally forgotten. \n\nThrough my research I found the glass seed bead. The glass seed-beads used here, like me, are a product of colonialism. The beads are not, and have never been made anywhere in Africa. Historically they were brought in from Europe on ships and exchanged for goods, and even slaves. The European countries which made up my family\u2019s colonial past, are those which historically brought the beads to Africa. This makes the beads as much a part of my own history, as native South Africans who traditionally have used them. \n\nThis carpet represents the unseen and misunderstood realities of my fellow South Africans, who I grew up with. The drawing represents a certain person\u2019s reality, their \u2018home\u2019, which is then translated into a hand-tufted carpet. I find myself struggling to find \u2018home\u2019, being neither comfortable back in South Africa, a tourist in my own country now, and never fitting in in the Netherlands either. This carpet becomes a physical cross-over of culture and craft. Hand tufted carpet in the Netherlands by the Textiel Museum, and beading hand made in South Africa.\n\nThis project attempts to question personal identity and to apprehend racial constructs through the navigation and realisation of objects that honour craft and the memory of those challenged by this between place, somewhere \u201ctussen wal en schip\u201d. ",
            "contributors": [
                {
                    "type": "standardizedContributor",
                    "first_name": "Pascale",
                    "last_name": "Theron",
                    "name": null,
                    "headline": "Freelance Artist and Designer at Pascale Theron Studio"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "title": "WHITE GUILT QUILT",
            "date": {
                "start": {
                    "month": 8,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2017
                },
                "end": {
                    "month": null,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": null
                }
            },
            "description": "My research for this project began, like many do, with a question concerning my identity. As a white South African, I am frequently asked bizarre questions. \u201cIf you\u2019re from Africa, then why aren\u2019t you black?\u201d\n\nThe European colonists in South Africa produced a racial stratification that evolved, furthered and then resulted in Apartheid. Apartheid then ended around the same time as when I was born. South Africa is a young country, that has undergone a drastic change within the last 25 years. This shows how young the democratic country really is, which has triggered a crisis in my own identity.\n\nAs a white woman growing up in modern South Africa, you are inadvertently brought up to believe that you are inherently European; momentarily trapped in a \u2018foreign\u2019 land. Now, living in the Netherlands, I find myself grappling to construct my personal identity and navigate my white privilege.\n\nThis blanket depicts the unseen people, my fellow South Africans who brought me up, the domestic workers. The blanket highlights details of the domestic situation in which these people work, and of which I am a product. Each figure is hand embroidered by the Mogalakwena community group in Limpopo, South Africa. The figures have been embroidered onto a thick woollen, traditional Dutch Aabe blanket.\n\nI should not be ashamed of being white, but in a country like South Africa, unfortunately the colour of your skin defines you more than you would like to admit. This skin-tight connection with colonisation makes me feel guilty, even though personally I know I had nothing to do with it, I was born into this privilege. Creating this blanket was my way of acknowledging my white privilege and all the history that it brings with it. ",
            "contributors": [
                {
                    "type": "standardizedContributor",
                    "first_name": "Pascale",
