                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "title": "TIME FLIES",
            "date": {
                "start": {
                    "month": 1,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2016
                },
                "end": {
                    "month": null,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": null
                }
            },
            "description": "Taxidermy is the art of preparing, stuffing and mounting the skins of animals after they have died. The aim of this project was to bring to life a dying craft, like Taxidermy, which over the years has lost its relevance in modern society. Through this project, its new relevance is as a really powerful tool in the popularisation of science. Taxidermied bird species become tasteful household objects that illustrate the irreplaceable nature of endangered species. It intrigues and interests, by creating a more elegant, desirable object. The aim is to have it displayed and sold at natural history museums, where one could buy it as a whimsical moving object that represents their support for the important and relevant research that is constantly being done at these museums. If taxidermy can contribute to educating a new generation of people, about biodiversity and the effect that we have on it, as well as contribute to a better life for living animals through funding, this is already one step closer to the future. Time is of the essence.",
            "contributors": [
